## Cross-linking between docs and API: `api:` links

This repository supports a custom link shorthand so the main docs (and API docs) can link into the generated API reference using progressive qualification, without writing full URLs.

Authoring format:

- Inline links: `[Text](api:Target)`
- (Optionally) reference-style links: `[Text][api:Target]`

Examples:

- `[Serializable](api:Serializable)`
- `[Serializable](api:internal.serializable.Serializable)`
- `[encode](api:Serializable.encode())`  (parentheses are allowed)
- `[SERIALIZATION_VERSION](api:Serializable.SERIALIZATION_VERSION)`
- `[get_available_backends](api:get_available_backends)`

Progressive qualification rules:

- A short target like `api:Serializable` resolves only if it is unique.
- If ambiguous, the build fails and you must add more qualification, e.g. `api:serializable.Serializable` or `api:internal.serializable.Serializable`.
- Fully-qualified names (`api:loqs.internal.serializable.Serializable`) always resolve when present.

Build behavior:

- Missing or ambiguous `api:` targets are a hard build failure.

How it works:

- The API build generates an inventory file at `docs/_api_inventory.json` containing:
  - all resolvable API anchors (modules/classes/functions/methods/attributes)
  - a suffix index to enable progressive qualification
- Both the main docs build and the API docs build rewrite `api:` links using this inventory.

Note: `docs/_api_inventory.json` is treated as a generated artifact and is cleaned up by `serve.py` after each build.

